---
import Base from '@/layouts/Base.astro';
import PageHeader from '@/components/PageHeader.astro';
import Callout from '@/components/Callout.astro';
import { site } from '@/lib/site';
---

<Base
  title="Privacy"
  description="No cookies, no trackers, no signups. I do not collect or store anything about you."
>
  <PageHeader
    eyebrow="Plain English"
    title="Privacy"
    intro="The short version is at the top. The longer version is below it, in plain English."
  />

  <div class="container-wide py-6 md:py-8">
    <div class="max-w-4xl">
      <Callout tone="success" title="The short version">
        <ul>
          <li>No cookies — none, not even one.</li>
          <li>No analytics, no tracking pixels, no ad networks.</li>
          <li>No newsletter signup, no email list, no contact form.</li>
          <li>I do not know who you are. I do not want to know who you are.</li>
          <li>
            When you use the MP lookup, your postcode is sent to a free non-profit service (<a
              href="https://postcodes.io"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
              target="_blank">postcodes.io</a
            >) and to the UK Parliament’s own service. It is not saved here.
          </li>
          <li>Your letter is built in your browser. It never reaches me.</li>
        </ul>
      </Callout>

      <article class="prose prose-neutral [&_a]:text-primary mt-8 max-w-4xl">
        <p>Last updated: <time datetime="2026-05-17">17 May 2026</time>.</p>

        <h2>Who I am</h2>
        <p>
          This site is run by <strong>{site.publisher.name}</strong>, a UK voter. Not a company, not
          a charity, not a CIC, not a political party. The contact address is
          <a href={`mailto:${site.publisher.email}`}>{site.publisher.email}</a>.
        </p>

        <h2>What I collect</h2>
        <p>Nothing personal. To be specific:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Postcode (only when you use the MP finder).</strong> Your postcode is sent from your
            browser to
            <a href="https://postcodes.io" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">postcodes.io</a
            >
            (a free non-profit) to find your constituency, and the constituency name is then sent to the
            UK Parliament Members service. Neither call goes through me. Nothing is stored on this site.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Letter contents.</strong> The letter is built in your browser using JavaScript. Your
            name, your town, anything you write — none of it is ever sent to me.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>IP address in edge logs.</strong> Like every site, mine is served from a CDN (Cloudflare).
            Their edge logs hold IP addresses for up to 7 days for abuse prevention. I do not read those
            logs and I cannot tie an IP to a person.
          </li>
        </ul>

        <h2>What I do not do</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>No cookies. Not even one. Open the dev tools and check.</li>
          <li>No Google Analytics, Plausible, Cabin or any other analytics product.</li>
          <li>No Facebook pixel, no Twitter embeds, no LinkedIn Insight tag, no TikTok.</li>
          <li>No Google Fonts at runtime. The fonts are self-hosted on this domain.</li>
          <li>No email list, no signup form, no newsletter.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Your rights</h2>
        <p>
          UK GDPR gives you rights of access, correction, deletion, and complaint. Because there is
          nothing held on you here, most of those rights are met by default. If you want to check,
          email <a href={`mailto:${site.publisher.email}`}>{site.publisher.email}</a>.
        </p>

        <h2>How to complain</h2>
        <p>
          You can complain to the UK Information Commissioner’s Office at any time —
          <a href="https://ico.org.uk/make-a-complaint/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank"
            >ico.org.uk/make-a-complaint</a
          >.
        </p>

        <h2 id="accessibility">Accessibility</h2>
        <p>
          The site aims to meet WCAG 2.2 AA. If you hit a barrier — a contrast issue, a missing
          label, anything that gets in your way — email
          <a href={`mailto:${site.publisher.email}`}>{site.publisher.email}</a>
          and I will fix it. Based on the AbilityNet model accessibility statement.
        </p>

        <h2>Updates to this notice</h2>
        <p>
          If anything material changes — for example, if I ever did start collecting emails — I will
          say so plainly at the top of this page, with a new “last updated” date.
        </p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </div>
</Base>
